MILINFANTRYDESC1: Infantry equipped with flintlock muskets. The backbone of any army, infantry are very cost effective and require less training and equipment than other unit types.
MILINFANTRYDESC2: Infantry equipped with muzzle-loaded rifles. The backbone of any army, infantry are very cost effective and require less training and equipment than other unit types.
MILINFANTRYDESC3: Infantry equipped with breech-loaded rifles. The backbone of any army, infantry are very cost effective and require less training and equipment than other unit types.
MILINFANTRYDESC4: Infantry equipped with early bolt action rifles. The backbone of any army, infantry are very cost effective and require less training and equipment than other unit types.
MILINFANTRYDESC5: Infantry equipped with repeating bolt action rifles and early machine guns. The backbone of any army, infantry are very cost effective and require less training and equipment than other unit types.
MILINFANTRYDESC6: Infantry equipped with a mixture of bolt action and semi-automatic rifles, as well as light machine guns. The backbone of any army, infantry are very cost effective and require less training and equipment than other unit types.
MILLIGHTINFBNDESC: A smaller unit of light infantry, attached to divisions for screening and reconnaissance purposes.
MILLIGHTINFDESC1: A variant of infantry equipped with early muzzle-loaded rifles. This type of infantry was trained to a higher standard and operated in loose order, acting as snipers, scouts, and being more efficient on rougher terrain.
MILLIGHTINFDESC2: An evolution of the light infantry concept, using more expensive and more accurate forms of the now wide-spread percussion cap rifles, but still operating in the same capacity as before.
MILLIGHTINFDESC3: The new breech-loading rifles allow screen infantry to punch well above their weight. Their improved degree of training means they can pick off the mostly green infantrymen of the regular regiments with ease, but their low numbers make it difficult to fight them head-on.
MILLIGHTINFDESC4: As the armament and tactics of the standard infantry encroached on the light infantry's niche, the training standard and specialization level of light infantry needed to improve. This new generation of light infantry is trained and equipped for rough terrain, and travels light for mobility and supply purposes.
MILLIGHTINFDESC5: Light infantry have learned to play to their strengths, sacrificing the heavier armament of the standard infantry for greater mobility and ease of use in colonial engagements. Despite this, the distinction between the two has become increasingly minimal.
MILLIGHTINFDESC6: Elite infantry with a proficiency for operation in extreme environments and rough terrain like mountains, marshes, and in cold and hot weather.
MILIRREGULARBRGDESC1: Barely trained infantry using a mixture of imported western muskets, ancient guns, and melee weapons. Commanded by the old warrior elite of eastern countries.
MILIRREGULARBRGDESC2: Militia called up for service, either bringing their own old muskets or issued some by the state. Used as auxilliaries in western armies, or the main bulk of the army in poor governments or somewhat westernized eastern countries.
MILIRREGULARBRGDESC7: Paramilitaries and militias that operate with a minimum of state-supplied equipment. While their standard of training is much higher than in the past, their combat effectiveness against regular armies is very poor. Useful for rebel suppression and light garrison duty.
LAWCONS1DESC: Men voluntarily enlist in the army. Slow recruitment unless you pay the soldiers high salaries. Soldier
LAWCONS2DESC: All able-bodied men are conscripted for 1 year. Conscripts up to 1% of the male population. Militancy from conscription can be reduced or eliminated by paying soldiers well, or being in certain scenarios, like other countries owning your core land.
LAWCONS3NAME: 2 Year Universal Conscription. Conscripts up to 1.5% of the male population
LAWCONS3DESC: All able-bodied men are conscripted for 2 years
LAWCONS4DESC: All able-bodied men are conscripted for 4 years
LAWCONS5DESC: All able-bodied men are conscripted for 6 years
LAWRES1DESC: Men volunteer to be part of the reserve force
LAWRES2DESC: Enlistees are required to remain in reserve for 2 years
LAWRES3DESC: Enlistees are required to remain in reserve for 3 years
LAWRES4DESC: Enlistees are required to remain in reserve for 6 years
LAWTAXLAND1DESC: 2% Tax on the wealth of rich pops per year
LAWTAXLAND2DESC: 3% Tax on the wealth of rich pops per year
LAWTAXLAND3DESC: 6% Tax on the wealth of rich pops per year
LAWTAXLAND4DESC: 8% Tax on the wealth of rich pops per year
LAWTAXLAND5DESC: 10% Tax on the wealth of rich pops per year
LAWTAXHEAD1DESC: Flat tax on each pop per year
LAWTAXHEAD2DESC: Flat tax on each pop per year
LAWTAXHEAD3DESC: Flat tax on each pop per year
LAWTAXINCOME1DESC: 2% tax on incomes above a minimum level
LAWTAXINCOME2DESC: 4% tax on incomes above a minimum level
LAWTAXINCOME3DESC: 8% tax on incomes above a minimum level
LAWTAXINCOME4DESC: 16% tax on incomes above a minimum level
LAWTAXINCOME5DESC: 32% tax on incomes above a minimum level
LAWSERFDOM1DESC: Peasants can be bound to the land and owned by the lords. In some countries like Russia, they are traded much like chattel slaves. With serfdom, laborers only recieve their life needs from RGO income. The nobility collects the rest.
LAWSERFDOM2DESC: All peasants are free and cannot be legally bound by any lord.
LAWCORVEE1DESC: Corvee is an ancient system of forced labor levied on peasants in lieu of taxes. With the corvee system in operation, the state does not need to pay pops for construction projects.
LAWCORVEE2DESC: Corvee system abolished. The state and nobility no longer have the right to force the peasantry to work for free.
LAWSLAVERY2DESC: Chattel slavery is only allowed in certain territories.
LAWSLAVERY3DESC: Slavery of all kinds is illegal.
LAWEMANCIPATION1DESC: Importing slaves is legal. Landowners will pay for slave pops from other countries with a legal slave trade, causing them to immigrate.
LAWEMANCIPATION2DESC: Importing slaves is illegal. Slave pops will grow faster due to better treatment.
LAWEMANCIPATION3DESC: Children of slaves become free. Slave pop growth will be redirected to laborer pop. Slave pops will shrink over time.
LAWSUFFRAGE2DESC: People who own land are allowed to vote.
LAWSUFFRAGE3DESC: People who pay a certain amount of taxes or rent a certain value of property can vote. Wealthier people's votes count more.
LAWSUFFRAGE4DESC: People who pay a certain amount of taxes or rent a certain value of property can vote.
LAWSUFFRAGE5DESC: All men can vote, but wealthier men's votes count more.
LAWUPPERHOUSE1DESC: No formal upper house exists, but the ruler is somewhat beholden to the elites of their country for practical reasons.
LAWUPPERHOUSE2DESC: The upper house consists of elites appointed by the monarch, with formal powers of parliament.
LAWUPPERHOUSE3DESC: The upper house is populated by elites selected by state governments, 2 per state.
LAWUPPERHOUSE4DESC: The upper house is elected by popular vote. Each state gets 2 members of the upper house.
LAWUPPERHOUSE5DESC: The upper house is elected by popular vote. Each state gets a share of the upper house proportional to their population.
LAWUPPERPOWER1DESC: The upper house has no formal powers, if it exists at all.
LAWUPPERPOWER2DESC: The upper house has the power to periodically introduce new laws. They will introduce reform based on movements, or based on the majority ideology.
LAWUPPERPOWER3DESC: The upper house votes on laws introduced by either house, if applicable, or the ruler.
LAWUPPERPOWER4DESC: The upper house has the power to veto taxation and spending suggested by the ruler.
LAWRULERPOWER1DESC: The ruler can unilaterally dissolve parliament at any time. Parliament is very weak and always approves what the ruler introduces.
LAWRULERPOWER2DESC: The ruler can veto any law parliament introduces. The people may become upset if the ruler vetoes popular laws.
LAWRULERPOWER3DESC: The ruler can veto any law, but if two thirds of parliament votes for the law, it will override the veto.
LAWLOWERHOUSE1DESC: A lower house doesn't formally exist.
LAWLOWERHOUSE2DESC: Lower house elected proportionally to population.
